== Polynomial Long Division ==

{{question-answer|question=130. Use polynomial long division to divide <math>P(x) = -x^4 + 2x^3 - 3x^2 - 1</math> by <math>D(x) = x+1</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>-x^3+3x^2-6x+6+\frac{-7}{x+1}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=131. Use polynomial long division to divide <math>P(x) = 2x^5 + x^4 + x - 3</math> by <math>D(x) = x^2-x+2</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>2x^3+3x^2-x-7+\frac{-4x+11}{x^2-x+2}</math>}}}}

== Polynomial Functions of Higher Degrees ==

{{question-answer|question=140. Use the [[w:Intermediate Value Theorem|Intermediate Value Theorem]] to show that the polynomial function <math>p(x) = x^6 − 3x^5 + 6x^2 − 1</math> has a zero in the interval <math>[-1,1]</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>p(0) < 0 < p(1)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=141. Given that the function <math>\displaystyle f(x) = \frac{x^6 − 10}{x^5+10x^2−x}</math> is continuous on the interval <math>[1,3]</math>, prove that it has a zero in that interval.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>f(1)< 0 < f(3)</math>}}}}

== Zeros of Polynomial Functions ==

{{question-answer|question=150. Find all zeroes of a polynomial function <math>p(x) = (x+4)^3(x^2-9)^2</math> and state the multiplicity of each zero.|answer={{noprint|1= -4 (3), -3 (2), 3 (2)}}}}
{{question-answer|question=151. Use the Descarte's Rule of Signs to state the possible numbers of positive and negative zeroes of the polynomial function <math>p(x) = x^4 - 3x^3 + x^2 - 1</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= 3 or 1 positive zeroes, 1 negative zero.}}}}
{{question-answer|question=152. Find the zeroes of the polynomial function <math>p(x) = x^3 - 8x^2 + 8x + 24</math> and state their multiplicity.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>6</math> (1), <math>1-\sqrt5</math> (1), <math>1+\sqrt5</math> (1)}}}}
{{question-answer|question=153. Find the zeroes of the polynomial function <math>p(x) = 2x^4 - 9x^3 - 2x^2 + 27x - 12</math> and state their multiplicity.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>1/2</math> (1), <math>4</math> (1), <math>-\sqrt3</math> (1), <math>\sqrt3</math> (1)}}}}

== Fundamental Theorem of Algebra ==

{{question-answer|question=160. Find a polynomial function of the lowest degree with roots <math>1,\ -1,\ 2+3i,\ 2-3i</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>p(x) = x^4 - 4x^3 + 12x^2 + 4x -13</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=161. Find all zeroes of a polynomial function <math>p(x) = 4x^4 - 4x^3 + 13x^2 - 12x +3</math>, given that it has a root <math>1/2</math> of multiplicity <math>2</math>. State the answer by rewriting the polynomial as a product of linear factors. |answer={{noprint|1= <math>p(x) = (x-1/2)^2(x+i\sqrt3)(x-i\sqrt3)</math>}}}}

== Inverse Functions ==

{{question-answer|question=170. Use composition of functions to determine whether <math>\displaystyle f(x) = \frac x2 - \frac32</math> and <math>g(x) = 2x + 3</math> are inverses of each other.|answer={{noprint|1= Yes}}}}
{{question-answer|question=171. Find the inverse of the function <math>f = \{(-2,4),(-1,1),(0,0),(1,1),(2,4)\}</math> or prove that it does not exist.|answer={{noprint|1= This function is not injective, since <math>f(-1) = f(1) = 1</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=172. Given <math>\displaystyle f(x) = \frac{x}{x-2}</math> find the inverse of <math>f</math>, and state the domains and the ranges for both <math>f</math> and <math>f^{-1}</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle f^{-1}(x) = \frac{2x}{x-1}</math>, <math>\mathop{\mathrm{dom}}(f) = \mathop{\mathrm{ran}}(f^{-1}) = \mathbb R - \{2\}</math>, <math>\mathop{\mathrm{ran}}(f) = \mathop{\mathrm{dom}}(f^{-1}) = \mathbb R - \{1\}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=173. Given <math>\displaystyle f(x) = \sqrt{4-x}</math> find the inverse of <math>f</math>, and state the domains and the ranges for both <math>f</math> and <math>f^{-1}</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle f^{-1}(x) = 4 - x^2</math>, <math>\mathop{\mathrm{dom}}(f) = \mathop{\mathrm{ran}}(f^{-1}) = (-\infty, 4]</math>, <math>\mathop{\mathrm{ran}}(f) = \mathop{\mathrm{dom}}(f^{-1}) = [0, \infty)</math>}}}}

