{{question-answer|question=223. Convert the radian measure <math>\displaystyle \frac{5\pi}6</math> into the exact degree measure.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>150^\circ</math>}}}}

== Right Triangle Trigonometry ==

{{question-answer|question=230. Find the values of <math>\sin(\theta)</math>, <math>\cos(\theta)</math>, <math>\tan(\theta)</math>, <math>\cot(\theta)</math>, <math>\sec(\theta)</math>, and <math>\csc(\theta)</math> if <math>\theta = \angle A</math> in the right triangle <math>ABC</math> with <math>\angle B = \pi/2</math> and side lengths <math>AB = 5</math> and <math>AC = 13</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\sin(\theta) = 12/13</math>, <math>\cos(\theta)=5/13</math>, <math>\tan(\theta)12/5</math>, <math>\cot(\theta)=5/12</math>, <math>\sec(\theta)=13/12</math>, and <math>\csc(\theta)=13/5</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=231. Let <math>\theta</math> be the acute angle in a right triangle and <math>\sin(\theta) = 0.3</math>. Find <math>\cos(\theta)</math> and <math>\tan(\theta)</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\cos(\theta) = \sqrt{0.91}</math> and <math>\displaystyle \tan(\theta) = \frac{0.3}{\sqrt{0.91}}</math>}}}}

== Trigonometric Functions of any Angle ==

{{question-answer|question=240. Find the value of <math>\sin(x)</math>, <math>\cos(x)</math>, <math>\tan(x)</math>, <math>\csc(x)</math>, <math>\sec(x)</math>, and <math>\cot(x)</math> for the angle, in standard position,
 whose terminal side passes through the point <math>(-3, -10)</math>.
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\sin(x) = -10/\sqrt{109}</math>, <math>\cos(x) = -3/\sqrt{109}</math>, <math>\tan(x) = 10/3</math>, <math>\csc(x) = -\sqrt{109}/10</math>, <math>\sec(x) = -\sqrt{109}/3</math>, and <math>\cot(x) = 0.3</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=241. Find <math>\cos(\theta)</math> if <math>\cot(\theta) = -1</math> and <math>\pi/2 < \theta < \pi</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>-1/\sqrt2</math>}}}}

