{{IB/Criterion|5.1.19|Compare the use of static and dynamic data structures.}}
{{IB/Criterion|5.1.20|Suggest a suitable structure for a given situation.}}

{{status|00%}}{{DISPLAYTITLE:Object-Oriented Programming}}
{{IB/Group_4/Computer_Science/Object-Oriented_Programming_Languages}}
Object-oriented design is another way of looking at the design process, which views a program from the standpoint of data rather than tasks. Because the functionality associated with this design process is often incorporated into high-level programming languages, we need to understand this design process before looking at specific high-level languages.
== Objects as a programming concept ==
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.1|Outline the general nature of an object}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.2|Distinguish between an object (definition, template, or class) and instantiation.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.3|Construct unified modelling language (UM) diagrams to represent object designs.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.4|Interpret UML diagrams.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.5|Describe the process of decomposition into several related objects.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.6|Describe the relationships between objects for a given problem.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.7|Outline the need to reduce dependencies between objects in a given problem.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.8|Construct related objects for a given problem.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.9|Explain the need for different data types to represent data items.}}
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.1.10|Describe how data items can be passed to and from actions as parameters.}}

== Features of OOP ==
{{IB_Computer_Science/Statement|D.2.1|Define the term encapsulation.}}
