{{sectstub}}


In HTML5, web apps are allowed to store persistent data on a device even if it is offline. W3C has published the [http://dev.w3.org/html5/webstorage/ Web Storage Specification]. In the Mozilla Developer Network, see the [https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/API/DOM/Storage DOM Storage Guide]. Apple provides a [https://developer.apple.com/library/safari/documentation/iPhone/Conceptual/SafariJSDatabaseGuide/Introduction/Introduction.html Safari Client-Side Storage and Offline Applications Programming Guide] in the Safari Developer Library.




{{Canvas 2D Web Apps BottomNav}}

{{sectstub}}


In HTML5, web apps are allowed to access the geolocation of a device. W3C has defined the [http://www.w3.org/TR/geolocation-API/ Geolocation API Specification]. In the Mozilla Developer Network, see [https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/WebAPI/Using_geolocation Using geolocation]. Apple provides information in the article [https://developer.apple.com/library/safari/documentation/AppleApplications/Reference/SafariWebContent/GettingGeographicalLocations/GettingGeographicalLocations.html Getting Geographic Location] in the Safari Developer Library.




